<button class="accordion">What is basic life support?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Basic Life Support, or BLS, generally refers to the type of care that first-responders, healthcare providers and public safety professionals provide to anyone who is experiencing cardiac arrest, respiratory distress or an obstructed airway. It requires knowledge and skills in cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR), using automated external defibrillators (AED) and relieving airway obstructions in patients of every age.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">What are the four elements of basic life support?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Basic Life Support (BLS) comprises the following elements:</p>
<p></p><li>Initial assessment</li>
<p></p><li>Airway maintenance</li>
<p></p><li>Chest compression</li>
<p></p><li>Expired air ventilation (rescue breathing).</li><p></p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">What is the sequence of steps in Basic life support?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The Basic Life Support survey includes four steps:</p>
<p></p><li>Check for a response – Shout "Are you okay?!" Do not be afraid to yell.</li>
<p></p><li>Call for help – Yell for help, telling others to call 999 and to bring an AED.</li>
<p></p><li>Check circulation – In adults, the best place to check for a pulse is the carotid artery.</li>
<p></p><li>Check rhythm – This step requires an AED.</li><p></p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">What is basic life support CPR?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>BLS is an abbreviation for Basic Life Support. It is merely another term for CPR and leans towards meaning healthcare provider level. Basic life support refers to maintaining an open airway and supporting breathing and circulation without the use of equipment other than a protective device.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">What are the seven steps of CPR?</button>
<div class="panel">
 <p>The seven steps of CPR are:</p>
<p></p><li>Position your hand (above)</li>
<p></p><li>Interlock fingers (above)</li>
<p></p><li>Give chest compressions (above)</li>
<p></p><li>Open the airway (above)</li>
<p></p><li>Give rescue breaths (above)</li>
<p></p><li>Watch your chest fall</li>
<p></p><li>Repeat chest compressions and rescue breaths.</li><p></p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">What is the purpose of basic life support?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The purpose of Basic Life Support is to maintain sufficient blood circulation and breathing through a clear airway. If you are responding to an emergency, having a basic life support certification will assure the patient that you are qualified to help them.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">What are the guidelines of basic life support?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Here are the guidelines for Basic Life Support:</p>
<p></p><li>Keep the compression rate of at least 100 minutes for all persons</li>
<p></p><li>Keep compression depth of between 2-2.4 inches for adults and children and about 1.5 inches for infants</li>
<p></p><li>Allow complete chest recoil after each compression. Minimise interruptions in CPR, except to use an AED or to change rescuer positions.</li><p></p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">What is the importance of basic life support?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The purpose of basic life support is to maintain sufficient blood circulation and breathing through a clear airway. If you are responding to an emergency, having a basic life support certification will assure the patient that you are qualified to help them.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">What is the benefit of basic life support?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>It can help people who are choking, drowning or are suffering from cardiac arrest, and it can make the difference between life and death for some people. Basic Life Support is included in all first aid training courses, along with related life-saving techniques and procedures such as cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR).</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">Can you take basic life support classes online?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>At the UK Red Cross, Basic Life Support online courses are easy to access and easy to complete. Online Basic life support classes split into interactive modules that you can take as your schedule permits.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">What compromises basic life support training?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Basic Life Support training covers basic mouth-to-mouth resuscitation and CPR for infants, children and adults. CPR stands for cardiopulmonary resuscitation. Generally, it involves chest compressions to help blood circulation.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">What are the options for basic life support training courses?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Basic Life Support (BLS) is available in two different training methods, including blended learning and classroom training.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">Can you renew basic life support?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Nowadays, health and social care organisations allow healthcare and social care staff to earn and renew their basic life support card either in person or online. If they choose the online option, they have to take an in-person skills test. However, plenty of respected organisations offer both basic life support certification and recertification entirely online.</p>
</div> 

<button class="accordion">Who is the intended audience for basic life support instructor training?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Our Basic Life Support instructor training is suitable for anyone who is looking to become, or renew as a CPR instructor.
</p>
</div> 

<button class="accordion">What is the minimum age to learn basic life support?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>There is no specific age requirement. Anyone who works in healthcare, social care and community settings can learn basic life support.
</p>
</div> 

<button class="accordion">Who should take basic life support courses?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Healthcare and social care professionals and staff must take the basic life support course as their job requires ensuring patient safety at all times.
</p>
</div> 

<button class="accordion">What are the types of basic life support training?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The different types of CPR and life-saving courses are as follows:</p>
<p></p><li>Basic Life Support CPR</li>
<p></p><li>Advanced Cardiac Life Support</li>
<p></p><li>Pediatric Advanced Life Support</li>
<p></p><li>Heartsaver First Aid & CPR.</li><p></p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">How long does it take to get basic life support certification?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The Basic Life Support certification course is designed to take about four hours, or a half-day, excluding breaks. That timeframe is projected based on the recommended instructor-student ratio, which covers one instructor, six students and two manikins.</p></div>

<button class="accordion">What is the purpose of basic life support training?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>This Basic Life Support course is designed to provide healthcare and social care professionals with the ability to recognise several life-threatening emergencies, provide CPR, use an AED, and relieve choking in a safe, timely and effective manner.</p></div>

<button class="accordion">What are the principles of emergency care?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>In spite of the variety of injuries possible, several principles of first aid apply to all emergencies, such as:</p>
<p></p><li>Aims</li>
<p></p><li>Protection against further injury</li>
<p></p><li>Preservation of life</li>
<p></p><li>Promotion of recovery</li>
<p></p><li>Prevention of injuries for people of any age</li>
<p></p><li>Promotion of healthy lifestyles.</li><p></p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">What is the purpose of rescue breathing?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The goal of rescue breathing is to add oxygen to the body when the victim is not able to breathe on their own. If a victim needs to get oxygen into their lungs, breathing life into them might be their only hope.</p></div>

<button class="accordion">What is an automated external defibrillator (AED)?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>An automated external defibrillator is a portable electronic device that automatically diagnoses the life-threatening cardiac arrhythmias of ventricular fibrillation and pulseless ventricular tachycardia.</p></div> 

<button class="accordion">How vital is basic life support, cpr and aed training?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>CPR/AED training is an essential resource in an emergency. Effective bystander CPR provided immediately after sudden cardiac arrest can double or triple a person's chances of survival. The training should include how to recognise a person experiencing sudden cardiac arrest, which often comes without symptoms.</p></div> 

<button class="accordion">What is pediatric resuscitation?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Respiratory failure and shock are the most common causes of cardiopulmonary arrest in the pediatric population. Their management, along with the management of other cardiac dysrhythmias, pulseless electrical activity (PEA), and asystole are essential goals of pediatric resuscitation.</p></div> 

<button class="accordion">What does mouth to mouth resuscitation involve?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Mouth to mouth resuscitation, a form of artificial ventilation, is the act of assisting or stimulating respiration in which a rescuer presses their mouth against that of the person to blow air into the lungs.</p></div> 

<button class="accordion">Do you stop compressions from giving breaths?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>You should not halt compressions to deliver breaths. The rule of thumb is to press hard and fast. You need to achieve 100 to 120 compressions per minute. You must not stop your compressions, but the person on respirations has to administer the breaths every eight to ten seconds.</p></div> 

<button class="accordion">What do you learn in basic life support?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The primary skills taught in the Basic Life Support course include basic mouth-to-mouth resuscitation and CPR. CPR stands for cardiopulmonary resuscitation and involves chest compressions to help blood circulation. Training will consist of CPR for infants, children, and adults as different procedures must be taken for each group.
</p></div> 

<button class="accordion">What are the three priorities of life support?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The three P's of First Aid are:</p>
<p></p><li>Preserve Life. As a first responder to any situation, your priority should be to preserve life.</li>
<p></p><li>Prevent Deterioration. Do what you can to keep the victim in stable condition until medical professionals arrive.</li>
<p></p><li>Promote Recovery.</li><p></p>
</div>

